{"questionId":"9067307","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">A student synthesized aspirin, acetylsalicylic acid, in a school laboratory.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img style=\"margin-right:auto;margin-left:auto;display:block;\" src=\"__IMG__/af1a8f4d885f34fb3ff17759315f51472889ddf2.png\" width=\"203\" height=\"273\"></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Outline how aspirin can be chemically modified to increase its solubility in water.</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">convert to a salt<br><em><strong>OR</strong></em><br>react with sodium hydroxide/NaOH&nbsp; <strong>[✔]</strong></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><strong> Note:</strong>&nbsp;Accept other reactions forming soluble salts. </span></em></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Accept “to ionize” but <strong>not</strong> “more polar”.</span></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9067307","referenceCode":"19M.3.sl.TZ2.15c","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Outline how aspirin can be chemically modified to increase its solubility in water.","paper":"3","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Options","Options","D: Medicinal chemistry","D.2 Aspirin and penicillin","Options","D: Medicinal chemistry"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}